[0m[49m[39m  188, 190[0m:[39m[49m ### Prerequisites
[0m[49m[39m  189, 191[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  190, 192[0m:[39m[49m | Requirement | Details |
[0m[49m[39m  191, 193[0m:[39m[49m |-------------|---------|
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 192     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m | **AWS Services** | Amazon SageMaker, Amazon S3, AWS Glue, Amazon Redshift, Amazon QuickSight, AWS Step Functions, AWS Lambda |
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 193     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m | **IAM Permissions** | `sagemaker:CreateTrainingJob`, `sagemaker:CreateProcessingJob`, `s3:GetObject`, `s3:PutObject`, `glue:StartJobRun`, `redshift:GetClusterCredentials`, `states:StartExecution`, `quicksight:*` |
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 194     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m | **BAA** | Required if patient-level utilization data is used (it usually is for gravity model estimation). Aggregate/de-identified data for the optimizer itself may not require BAA, but the upstream data pipeline does. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      194[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Services** | Amazon SageMaker, Amazon S3, AWS Glue, Amazon Redshift (Serverless recommended), Amazon QuickSight, AWS Step Functions, AWS Lambda |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      195[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **IAM Permissions** | `sagemaker:CreateProcessingJob`, `s3:GetObject`, `s3:PutObject`, `glue:StartJobRun`, `redshift:GetClusterCredentials`, `states:StartExecution`, `quicksight:CreateIngestion`, `quicksight:DescribeIngestion`, `quicksight:UpdateDataSet`, `quicksight:DescribeDashboard` (scoped to specific resource ARNs) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      196[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **BAA** | Required. The gravity model estimation step uses patient-level data with geographic identifiers (ZIP code of residence + facility visited), which constitutes PHI. All services in the upstream pipeline (Redshift, SageMaker, S3 buckets holding patient origin data) must be covered. Once gravity model parameters are estimated, the optimizer itself operates on zone-level demand aggregates (not patient-level records). Ensure the SageMaker processing job output contains no patient-level records. |
[0m[49m[39m  195, 197[0m:[39m[49m | **Encryption** | S3: SSE-KMS for all buckets; Redshift: encrypted cluster; SageMaker: KMS-encrypted volumes and network isolation; all transit over TLS |
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 196     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m | **VPC** | SageMaker jobs in private subnets with VPC endpoints for S3 and CloudWatch. Redshift in private subnet. No public internet access for compute resources touching patient data. |
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 197     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m | **CloudTrail** | Enabled for all API calls. Optimization runs are auditable (who ran what scenario with what assumptions). |
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 198     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m | **Solver Licensing** | If using Gurobi or CPLEX: license server or token-based licensing configured for SageMaker instances. Gurobi offers cloud licensing; CPLEX supports token servers. Budget $10K-$50K/year for enterprise solver licenses. |
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 199     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m | **Cost Estimate** | SageMaker ml.m5.4xlarge for solver execution: ~$0.92/hour. Typical multi-scenario run: 4-8 hours. Monthly cost (weekly runs): ~$200-$600 compute. Redshift ra3.xlplus (2 nodes): ~$1,500/month. Total infrastructure: ~$2,000-$3,000/month. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      198[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **VPC** | SageMaker jobs in private subnets. VPC endpoints required: S3 (Gateway), CloudWatch Logs (Interface), SageMaker API (Interface), SageMaker Runtime (Interface), Step Functions (Interface), Glue (Interface), KMS (Interface). Lambda functions calling AWS services from within the VPC require these endpoints or a NAT Gateway. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      199[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **CloudTrail** | Enabled for all API calls. CloudTrail captures infrastructure-level audit (who started which SageMaker job). For decision-level audit (what scenarios were run, what parameters were used, what the optimizer recommended), log scenario configurations and solution summaries to a dedicated S3 audit bucket with object lock (WORM) enabled. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      200[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Solver Licensing** | If using Gurobi or CPLEX: for no-internet VPC configurations, use a self-hosted license server (Gurobi token server or CPLEX ILM server) deployed in the same VPC. Gurobi's Web License Service (WLS) requires outbound HTTPS to license.gurobi.com; if your VPC prohibits this, use a local license file or token server. Verify that solver telemetry/usage reporting is disabled or does not transmit model content. For open-source solvers (HiGHS, CBC), no licensing infrastructure is needed. Budget $10K-$50K/year for enterprise commercial solver licenses. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      201[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Cost Estimate** | SageMaker ml.m5.4xlarge for solver execution: ~$0.92/hour. Typical multi-scenario run: 4-8 hours. Monthly cost (weekly runs): ~$200-$600 compute. Redshift Serverless: ~$50-$200 per optimization cycle. Total infrastructure: ~$500-$1,500/month for quarterly runs. |
[0m[49m[39m  200, 202[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  201, 203[0m:[39m[49m ### Ingredients
[0m[49m[39m  202, 204[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  203, 205[0m:[39m[49m | AWS Service | Role |
[0m[49m[39m  204, 206[0m:[39m[49m |------------|------|
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 205     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m | **Amazon SageMaker** | Model development (notebooks), solver execution (training jobs), demand forecasting (processing jobs) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      207[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon SageMaker** | Model development (notebooks), solver execution (processing jobs), demand forecasting (processing jobs) |
[0m[49m[39m  206, 208[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon S3** | Data lake for inputs, model artifacts, optimization results |
[0m[49m[39m  207, 209[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS Glue** | ETL from source systems; data quality checks; schema normalization |
[0m[49m[39m  208, 210[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon Redshift** | Analytical warehouse for historical utilization, patient origin, financial data |
[0m[49m[39m  209, 211[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon QuickSight** | Executive dashboards: maps, scenario comparisons, sensitivity analysis |
[0m[49m[39m  210, 212[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS Step Functions** | Pipeline orchestration across data prep, forecasting, optimization, reporting |
[0m[49m[39m  211, 213[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS Lambda** | Scenario configuration, result post-processing, API layer |
[0m[49m[39m  212, 214[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS KMS** | Encryption key management for all data at rest |
[0m[49m[39m  213, 215[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon CloudWatch** | Monitoring solver execution time, pipeline health, cost tracking |
[0m[49m[39m  214, 216[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  215, 217[0m:[39m[49m ### Code
[0m[49m[39m  216, 218[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  217, 219[0m:[39m[49m #### Walkthrough
[0m[49m[39m  218, 220[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  219, 221[0m:[39m[49m **Step 1: Data integration and demand zone construction.** Before you can optimize anything, you need to define the geography. Health system network design operates on "demand zones": geographic units (typically ZIP codes or census tracts) where you can estimate current and future demand for each service line. This step pulls patient origin data from the EHR (where do current patients come from?), overlays demographic projections, and constructs the demand matrix: how many patients of each type will need care in each zone over the planning horizon. Skip this step and you're optimizing against fantasy numbers. The quality of your demand estimates is the single biggest determinant of whether the optimization output is useful or misleading.
[0m[49m[39m  220, 222[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  221, 223[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  222, 224[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION build_demand_zones(patient_origin_data, demographic_projections, service_lines):
[0m[49m[39m  223, 225[0m:[39m[49m     // Define geographic demand zones from patient origin patterns.
[0m[49m[39m  224, 226[0m:[39m[49m     // Each zone represents a geographic area with estimable demand.
[0m[49m[39m  225, 227[0m:[39m[49m     // Typically ZIP codes or census tracts, depending on data granularity.
[0m[49m[39m  226, 228[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  227, 229[0m:[39m[49m     zones = extract unique geographic units from patient_origin_data
[0m[49m[39m  228, 230[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  229, 231[0m:[39m[49m     // For each zone, calculate current demand by service line.
[0m[49m[39m  230, 232[0m:[39m[49m     // "Demand" here means total utilization (your patients + competitor patients).
[0m[49m[39m  231, 233[0m:[39m[49m     // Your patient origin data shows YOUR volume; you need market share estimates
[0m[49m[39m  232, 234[0m:[39m[49m     // to infer total market demand.
[0m[49m[39m  233, 235[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  234, 236[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each zone in zones:
[0m[49m[39m  235, 237[0m:[39m[49m         FOR each service_line in service_lines:
[0m[49m[39m  236, 238[0m:[39m[49m             // Current volume from your system
[0m[49m[39m  237, 239[0m:[39m[49m             your_volume = count patients from zone using service_line
[0m[49m[39m  238, 240[0m:[39m[49m             
[0m[49m[39m  239, 241[0m:[39m[49m             // Estimate total market demand using market share
[0m[49m[39m  240, 242[0m:[39m[49m             // Market share comes from claims data or state discharge databases
[0m[49m[39m  241, 243[0m:[39m[49m             estimated_market_share = lookup market share for zone, service_line
[0m[49m[39m  242, 244[0m:[39m[49m             total_demand_current = your_volume / estimated_market_share
[0m[49m[39m  243, 245[0m:[39m[49m             
[0m[49m[39m  244, 246[0m:[39m[49m             // Project forward using demographic growth rates
[0m[49m[39m  245, 247[0m:[39m[49m             // Different service lines grow at different rates
[0m[49m[39m  246, 248[0m:[39m[49m             // (e.g., joint replacement grows faster in aging populations)
[0m[49m[39m  247, 249[0m:[39m[49m             growth_rate = lookup growth rate for zone, service_line from demographic_projections
[0m[49m[39m  248, 250[0m:[39m[49m             
[0m[49m[39m  249, 251[0m:[39m[49m             FOR each year in planning_horizon:
[0m[49m[39m  250, 252[0m:[39m[49m                 projected_demand[zone][service_line][year] = 
[0m[49m[39m  251, 253[0m:[39m[49m                     total_demand_current * (1 + growth_rate) ^ year
[0m[49m[39m  252, 254[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  253, 255[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN projected_demand, zones
[0m[49m[39m  254, 256[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  255, 257[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  256, 258[0m:[39m[49m **Step 2: Gravity model estimation.** Patients don't go to the nearest facility. They make choices. The gravity model captures those choices by estimating how "attractive" each facility is to patients in each zone, accounting for distance, facility size, service breadth, and reputation. The parameters are estimated from historical patient flow data: where did patients actually go, and how far did they travel? This model is what allows the optimizer to predict how patient flows will shift when you open a new facility or add a service line. Without it, you're assuming patients will behave in ways they demonstrably don't.
[0m[49m[39m  257, 259[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  258, 260[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  259, 261[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION estimate_gravity_model(patient_flows, facility_attributes, zone_attributes):
[0m[49m[39m  260, 262[0m:[39m[49m     // The gravity model predicts the probability that a patient in zone z
[0m[49m[39m  261, 263[0m:[39m[49m     // chooses facility f. The classic form:
[0m[49m[39m  262, 264[0m:[39m[49m     //
[0m[49m[39m  263, 265[0m:[39m[49m     //   P(z -> f) = attractiveness(f) * distance_decay(z, f) / 
[0m[49m[39m  264, 266[0m:[39m[49m     //               sum over all facilities g of [attractiveness(g) * distance_decay(z, g)]
[0m[49m[39m  265, 267[0m:[39m[49m     //
[0m[49m[39m  266, 268[0m:[39m[49m     // attractiveness(f) = function of bed count, service breadth, quality scores
[0m[49m[39m  267, 269[0m:[39m[49m     // distance_decay(z, f) = exp(-beta * travel_time(z, f))
[0m[49m[39m  268, 270[0m:[39m[49m     //
[0m[49m[39m  269, 271[0m:[39m[49m     // beta (distance sensitivity) varies by service line:
[0m[49m[39m  270, 272[0m:[39m[49m     //   - Primary care: high beta (patients won't travel far)
[0m[49m[39m  271, 273[0m:[39m[49m     //   - Cardiac surgery: low beta (patients will travel for specialized care)
[0m[49m[39m  272, 274[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  273, 275[0m:[39m[49m     // Calculate travel time matrix: every zone to every facility
[0m[49m[39m  274, 276[0m:[39m[49m     travel_times = compute drive time from centroid of each zone to each facility
[0m[49m[39m  275, 277[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  276, 278[0m:[39m[49m     // Estimate model parameters from historical patient flows
[0m[49m[39m  277, 279[0m:[39m[49m     // This is a maximum likelihood estimation problem
[0m[49m[39m  278, 280[0m:[39m[49m     // (logistic regression variant, specifically a conditional logit model)
[0m[49m[39m  279, 281[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  280, 282[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each service_line:
[0m[49m[39m  281, 283[0m:[39m[49m         // Observed choices: which facility did each patient actually choose?
[0m[49m[39m  282, 284[0m:[39m[49m         observed_choices = extract patient facility choices for service_line
[0m[49m[39m  283, 285[0m:[39m[49m         
[0m[49m[39m  284, 286[0m:[39m[49m         // Estimate beta (distance sensitivity) and attractiveness weights
[0m[49m[39m  285, 287[0m:[39m[49m         // using maximum likelihood on the observed choice data
[0m[49m[39m  286, 288[0m:[39m[49m         parameters[service_line] = fit conditional logit model:
[0m[49m[39m  287, 289[0m:[39m[49m             dependent variable = facility chosen
[0m[49m[39m  288, 290[0m:[39m[49m             features = travel_time, bed_count, service_breadth, quality_score
[0m[49m[39m  289, 291[0m:[39m[49m             data = observed_choices
[0m[49m[39m  290, 292[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  291, 293[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN parameters, travel_times
[0m[49m[39m  292, 294[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  293, 295[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  294, 296[0m:[39m[49m **Step 3: Model formulation.** This is the intellectual core. You're translating the business problem into mathematics. Every strategic question ("Should we build a cancer center at location X?") becomes a binary variable. Every constraint ("We can't spend more than $400M") becomes a linear inequality. Every objective ("Maximize net revenue while maintaining access") becomes a function to optimize. The formulation quality determines whether the solver produces useful answers or garbage. A poorly formulated model might be technically optimal but strategically meaningless.
[0m[49m[39m  295, 297[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  296, 298[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  297, 299[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION formulate_network_model(zones, facilities, service_lines, parameters, constraints):
[0m[49m[39m  298, 300[0m:[39m[49m     // Create the optimization model
[0m[49m[39m  299, 301[0m:[39m[49m     model = new MixedIntegerProgram()
[0m[49m[39m  300, 302[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  301, 303[0m:[39m[49m     // === DECISION VARIABLES ===
[0m[49m[39m  302, 304[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  303, 305[0m:[39m[49m     // Binary: should facility f offer service line s?
[0m[49m[39m  304, 306[0m:[39m[49m     // This is the core strategic decision.
[0m[49m[39m  305, 307[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each facility f, service_line s:
[0m[49m[39m  306, 308[0m:[39m[49m         offer[f][s] = model.add_binary_variable("offer_{f}_{s}")
[0m[49m[39m  307, 309[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  308, 310[0m:[39m[49m     // Binary: should we open/expand facility f? (for new or expanded facilities)
[0m[49m[39m  309, 311[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each candidate_facility f:
[0m[49m[39m  310, 312[0m:[39m[49m         open[f] = model.add_binary_variable("open_{f}")
[0m[49m[39m  311, 313[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  312, 314[0m:[39m[49m     // Integer: capacity tier at facility f for service line s
[0m[49m[39m  313, 315[0m:[39m[49m     // (e.g., 0 = none, 1 = small, 2 = medium, 3 = large)
[0m[49m[39m  314, 316[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each facility f, service_line s:
[0m[49m[39m  315, 317[0m:[39m[49m         capacity_tier[f][s] = model.add_integer_variable("cap_{f}_{s}", min=0, max=3)
[0m[49m[39m  316, 318[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  317, 319[0m:[39m[49m     // Continuous: patient flow from zone z to facility f for service line s
[0m[49m[39m  318, 320[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each zone z, facility f, service_line s:
[0m[49m[39m  319, 321[0m:[39m[49m         flow[z][f][s] = model.add_continuous_variable("flow_{z}_{f}_{s}", min=0)
[0m[49m[39m  320, 322[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  321, 323[0m:[39m[49m     // === OBJECTIVE FUNCTION ===
[0m[49m[39m  322, 324[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  323, 325[0m:[39m[49m     // Maximize: weighted combination of net revenue and access coverage
[0m[49m[39m  324, 326[0m:[39m[49m     net_revenue = SUM over f, s of:
[0m[49m[39m  325, 327[0m:[39m[49m         (revenue_per_case[s] * total_flow_to[f][s]) - fixed_cost[f][s] * offer[f][s]
[0m[49m[39m  326, 328[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  327, 329[0m:[39m[49m     access_coverage = SUM over z, s of:
[0m[49m[39m  328, 330[0m:[39m[49m         (flow[z][nearest_facility(z,s)][s] / demand[z][s])  // fraction served within threshold
[0m[49m[39m  329, 331[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  330, 332[0m:[39m[49m     model.maximize(weight_financial * net_revenue + weight_access * access_coverage)
[0m[49m[39m  331, 333[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  332, 334[0m:[39m[49m     // === CONSTRAINTS ===
[0m[49m[39m  333, 335[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  334, 336[0m:[39m[49m     // Budget constraint: total capital cannot exceed available funds
[0m[49m[39m  335, 337[0m:[39m[49m     model.add_constraint(
[0m[49m[39m  336, 338[0m:[39m[49m         SUM over f of (capital_cost[f] * open[f]) <= total_budget
[0m[49m[39m  337, 339[0m:[39m[49m     )
[0m[49m[39m  338, 340[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  339, 341[0m:[39m[49m     // Capacity constraint: volume cannot exceed capacity at any facility
[0m[49m[39m  340, 342[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each facility f, service_line s:
[0m[49m[39m  341, 343[0m:[39m[49m         model.add_constraint(
[0m[49m[39m  342, 344[0m:[39m[49m             SUM over z of flow[z][f][s] <= capacity[capacity_tier[f][s]]
[0m[49m[39m  343, 345[0m:[39m[49m         )
[0m[49m[39m  344, 346[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  345, 347[0m:[39m[49m     // Demand satisfaction: all demand must be assigned somewhere
[0m[49m[39m  346, 348[0m:[39m[49m     // (including "leakage" to competitors, modeled as a dummy facility)
[0m[49m[39m  347, 349[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each zone z, service_line s:
[0m[49m[39m  348, 350[0m:[39m[49m         model.add_constraint(
[0m[49m[39m  349, 351[0m:[39m[49m             SUM over f of flow[z][f][s] == demand[z][s]
[0m[49m[39m  350, 352[0m:[39m[49m         )
[0m[49m[39m  351, 353[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  352, 354[0m:[39m[49m     // Flow consistency with gravity model:
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 353     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m     // Patient flows must be consistent with choice probabilities
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 354     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m     // (This links the optimization to realistic patient behavior)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      355[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Patient flows must be consistent with choice probabilities.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      356[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // NOTE: These probabilities are pre-computed based on the current network.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      357[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // When the optimizer opens or closes facilities, the true probabilities change.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      358[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // The standard fix is iterative balancing: solve, recompute probabilities for
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      359[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // the recommended network, re-solve, repeat until convergence (typically 3-5
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      360[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // iterations). This is omitted here for clarity but is essential for solution
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      361[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // quality in production.
[0m[49m[39m  355, 362[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each zone z, facility f, service_line s:
[0m[49m[39m  356, 363[0m:[39m[49m         model.add_constraint(
[0m[49m[39m  357, 364[0m:[39m[49m             flow[z][f][s] <= demand[z][s] * choice_probability(z, f, s, parameters)
[0m[49m[39m  358, 365[0m:[39m[49m         )
[0m[49m[39m  359, 366[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  360, 367[0m:[39m[49m     // Service line dependencies: can't offer cardiac surgery without cardiac ICU
[0m[49m[39m  361, 368[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each (service_a, requires_service_b) in dependency_rules:
[0m[49m[39m  362, 369[0m:[39m[49m         FOR each facility f:
[0m[49m[39m  363, 370[0m:[39m[49m             model.add_constraint(offer[f][service_a] <= offer[f][requires_service_b])
[0m[49m[39m  364, 371[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  365, 372[0m:[39m[49m     // Minimum volume thresholds: if you offer a service, you must hit minimum volume
[0m[49m[39m  366, 373[0m:[39m[49m     // (This prevents the optimizer from spreading volume too thin)
[0m[49m[39m  367, 374[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each facility f, service_line s:
[0m[49m[39m  368, 375[0m:[39m[49m         model.add_constraint(
[0m[49m[39m  369, 376[0m:[39m[49m             SUM over z of flow[z][f][s] >= minimum_volume[s] * offer[f][s]
[0m[49m[39m  370, 377[0m:[39m[49m         )
[0m[49m[39m  371, 378[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  372, 379[0m:[39m[49m     // Certificate of Need (CON) constraints: some states require regulatory approval
[0m[49m[39m  373, 380[0m:[39m[49m     // for new services or capacity expansions
[0m[49m[39m  374, 381[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each (facility, service) in con_required_list:
[0m[49m[39m  375, 382[0m:[39m[49m         model.add_constraint(offer[facility][service] <= con_approved[facility][service])
[0m[49m[39m  376, 383[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  377, 384[0m:[39m[49m     // Workforce constraints: can't staff what you can't recruit
[0m[49m[39m  378, 385[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each facility f, service_line s:
[0m[49m[39m  379, 386[0m:[39m[49m         model.add_constraint(
[0m[49m[39m  380, 387[0m:[39m[49m             required_physicians[s] * offer[f][s] <= available_physicians[f][s]
[0m[49m[39m  381, 388[0m:[39m[49m         )
[0m[49m[39m  382, 389[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  383, 390[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN model
[0m[49m[39m  384, 391[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  385, 392[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  386, 393[0m:[39m[49m **Step 4: Multi-scenario optimization.** No single demand forecast is reliable over a 10-year horizon. This step runs the optimization under multiple plausible futures and identifies which decisions are robust (good in most scenarios) versus which are contingent (great in one scenario, bad in another). Executives need to know: "Building the cancer center is a good idea regardless of growth assumptions. But the rural hospital conversion only makes sense if population decline continues." That's the kind of insight scenario analysis provides.
[0m[49m[39m  387, 394[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  388, 395[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  389, 396[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION run_scenario_analysis(base_model, scenarios):
[0m[49m[39m  390, 397[0m:[39m[49m     // Each scenario modifies demand projections, growth rates, 
[0m[49m[39m  391, 398[0m:[39m[49m     // competitive assumptions, or regulatory environment.
[0m[49m[39m  392, 399[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  393, 400[0m:[39m[49m     results = empty map
[0m[49m[39m  394, 401[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  395, 402[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each scenario in scenarios:
[0m[49m[39m  396, 403[0m:[39m[49m         // Clone the base model and apply scenario-specific modifications
[0m[49m[39m  397, 404[0m:[39m[49m         scenario_model = copy(base_model)
[0m[49m[39m  398, 405[0m:[39m[49m         
[0m[49m[39m  399, 406[0m:[39m[49m         // Adjust demand based on scenario assumptions
[0m[49m[39m  400, 407[0m:[39m[49m         // e.g., "high growth" scenario increases demand projections by 20%
[0m[49m[39m  401, 408[0m:[39m[49m         // e.g., "competitor entry" scenario reduces market share in affected zones
[0m[49m[39m  402, 409[0m:[39m[49m         apply_scenario_adjustments(scenario_model, scenario.demand_multipliers)
[0m[49m[39m  403, 410[0m:[39m[49m         apply_scenario_adjustments(scenario_model, scenario.market_share_changes)
[0m[49m[39m  404, 411[0m:[39m[49m         
[0m[49m[39m  405, 412[0m:[39m[49m         // Solve the modified model
[0m[49m[39m  406, 413[0m:[39m[49m         solution = solve(scenario_model, 
[0m[49m[39m  407, 414[0m:[39m[49m                         solver = "gurobi",  // or "highs" for open-source
[0m[49m[39m  408, 415[0m:[39m[49m                         time_limit = 3600,  // 1 hour max per scenario
[0m[49m[39m  409, 416[0m:[39m[49m                         mip_gap = 0.02)     // accept solutions within 2% of optimal
[0m[49m[39m  410, 417[0m:[39m[49m         
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      418[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Handle infeasibility: if no feasible solution exists, compute the
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      419[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Irreducible Infeasible Subsystem (IIS) to identify conflicting constraints.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      420[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Most commercial solvers provide this (Gurobi: model.computeIIS(),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      421[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // CPLEX: conflict refiner). Present conflicting constraints to decision-makers:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      422[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // "The budget and minimum volume constraints cannot both be satisfied."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      423[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF solution.status == INFEASIBLE:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      424[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             iis = compute_irreducible_infeasible_subsystem(scenario_model)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      425[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             results[scenario.name] = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      426[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 status: "infeasible",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      427[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 conflicting_constraints: iis,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      428[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 recommendation: "Relax budget or minimum volume thresholds"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      429[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      430[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             CONTINUE
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      431[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         
[0m[49m[39m  411, 432[0m:[39m[49m         results[scenario.name] = {
[0m[49m[39m  412, 433[0m:[39m[49m             objective_value: solution.objective,
[0m[49m[39m  413, 434[0m:[39m[49m             facility_decisions: extract open/close decisions from solution,
[0m[49m[39m  414, 435[0m:[39m[49m             service_line_decisions: extract offer decisions from solution,
[0m[49m[39m  415, 436[0m:[39m[49m             patient_flows: extract flow variables from solution,
[0m[49m[39m  416, 437[0m:[39m[49m             financial_projections: compute revenue/cost from solution,
[0m[49m[39m  417, 438[0m:[39m[49m             access_metrics: compute coverage metrics from solution
[0m[49m[39m  418, 439[0m:[39m[49m         }
[0m[49m[39m  419, 440[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  420, 441[0m:[39m[49m     // Identify robust decisions: same in all (or most) scenarios
[0m[49m[39m  421, 442[0m:[39m[49m     robust_decisions = find decisions that appear in ALL scenario solutions
[0m[49m[39m  422, 443[0m:[39m[49m     contingent_decisions = find decisions that differ across scenarios
[0m[49m[39m  423, 444[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  424, 445[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN results, robust_decisions, contingent_decisions
[0m[49m[39m  425, 446[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  426, 447[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  427, 448[0m:[39m[49m **Step 5: Sensitivity analysis and result presentation.** The optimization output is a set of recommended decisions. But executives don't just want "the answer." They want to understand how sensitive that answer is to key assumptions. If the cancer center recommendation flips when you change the growth rate by 5%, that's a fragile recommendation. If it holds across a wide range of assumptions, that's a robust one. This step computes sensitivity metrics and packages everything for the decision support dashboard.
[0m[49m[39m  428, 449[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  429, 450[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  430, 451[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION compute_sensitivity_and_present(results, key_parameters):
[0m[49m[39m  431, 452[0m:[39m[49m     // For each key assumption, vary it and see if the optimal solution changes
[0m[49m[39m  432, 453[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  433, 454[0m:[39m[49m     sensitivity_report = empty map
[0m[49m[39m  434, 455[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  435, 456[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each parameter in key_parameters:
[0m[49m[39m  436, 457[0m:[39m[49m         // Vary the parameter across a range (e.g., +/- 20% from base case)
[0m[49m[39m  437, 458[0m:[39m[49m         FOR each variation in [0.8, 0.9, 1.0, 1.1, 1.2] * parameter.base_value:
[0m[49m[39m  438, 459[0m:[39m[49m             modified_solution = re-solve model with parameter = variation
[0m[49m[39m  439, 460[0m:[39m[49m             
[0m[49m[39m  440, 461[0m:[39m[49m             // Record whether key decisions changed
[0m[49m[39m  441, 462[0m:[39m[49m             sensitivity_report[parameter.name][variation] = {
[0m[49m[39m  442, 463[0m:[39m[49m                 decisions_changed: compare to base solution,
[0m[49m[39m  443, 464[0m:[39m[49m                 objective_impact: modified_solution.objective - base_solution.objective
[0m[49m[39m  444, 465[0m:[39m[49m             }
[0m[49m[39m  445, 466[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  446, 467[0m:[39m[49m     // Package results for dashboard
[0m[49m[39m  447, 468[0m:[39m[49m     dashboard_output = {
[0m[49m[39m  448, 469[0m:[39m[49m         recommended_network: base solution facility and service decisions,
[0m[49m[39m  449, 470[0m:[39m[49m         scenario_comparison: side-by-side financial and access metrics,
[0m[49m[39m  450, 471[0m:[39m[49m         robust_decisions: decisions stable across all scenarios,
[0m[49m[39m  451, 472[0m:[39m[49m         contingent_decisions: decisions that depend on assumptions,
[0m[49m[39m  452, 473[0m:[39m[49m         sensitivity_charts: parameter sensitivity for key decisions,
[0m[49m[39m  453, 474[0m:[39m[49m         access_maps: geographic coverage maps for each scenario,
[0m[49m[39m  454, 475[0m:[39m[49m         financial_summary: NPV, IRR, payback period for capital investments,
[0m[49m[39m  455, 476[0m:[39m[49m         implementation_timeline: phased rollout based on dependencies
[0m[49m[39m  456, 477[0m:[39m[49m     }
[0m[49m[39m  457, 478[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  458, 479[0m:[39m[49m     // Write results to S3 for QuickSight consumption
[0m[49m[39m  459, 480[0m:[39m[49m     write dashboard_output to S3 as structured JSON/Parquet
[0m[49m[39m  460, 481[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  461, 482[0m:[39m[49m     // Trigger QuickSight dataset refresh
[0m[49m[39m  462, 483[0m:[39m[49m     trigger QuickSight SPICE refresh for network design dataset
[0m[49m[39m  463, 484[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  464, 485[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN dashboard_output
[0m[49m[39m  465, 486[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  466, 487[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  467, 488[0m:[39m[49m > **Curious how this looks in Python?** The pseudocode above covers the concepts. If you'd like to see sample Python code that demonstrates these patterns using boto3 and PuLP/Gurobi, check out the [Python Example](chapter14.10-python-example). It walks through each step with inline comments and notes on what you'd need to change for a real deployment.
[0m[49m[39m  468, 489[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  469, 490[0m:[39m[49m ### Expected Results
[0m[49m[39m  470, 491[0m:[39m[49m 
